Hereâ€™s why these two books are secret weapons for technologists who want to spark passion, and not only &ldquo;convince with data&rdquo;:
ğŸ”¥ The Core Tension: Kahnemanâ€™s Systems vs. Sutherlandâ€™s &ldquo;Psycho-Logic&rdquo; Kahneman maps how we decide: System 1 (intuitive, emotional) and System 2 (logical, deliberate). Engineers adore System 2â€”it feels safe, optimized, &ldquo;correct.&rdquo; Sutherland rebels: &ldquo;Logic is a rear-view mirror&rdquo;. He argues System 1 drives 90% of decisions, yet we design products/processes for System 2. Result? &ldquo;Factually perfect but emotionally sterile&rdquo; interactions that disengage usersâ€”and teams. ğŸ§‘ğŸ¦¯ Engineerâ€™s blind spot: We solve for efficiency, not for the human experience of the solution. âš—ï¸ 3 &ldquo;Alchemical&rdquo; Rules Every Tech Team Should Steal 1. &ldquo;The Opposite of a Good Idea Can Also Be a Good Idea&rdquo;
Example: Red Bull succeeded because it tasted awful + was overpricedâ€”signalling &ldquo;extreme energy,&rdquo; not just &ldquo;beverage.&rdquo; ğŸ* For engineers: Sometimes a &ldquo;flaw&rdquo; (e.g., slower load time for suspense) creates delight. Not every bug needs fixing.* 2. &ldquo;Donâ€™t Design for Average&rdquo; Extreme users reveal more than the &ldquo;rational&rdquo; middle. Example: The sandwich was invented for a gambler who refused to leave cards for a meal.
â‡² For engineers: Personas are dead. Obsess over edge casesâ€”theyâ€™re innovation gold, and averages are a deadly boring and mediocre ground to be placed. 3. &ldquo;A Flower Is Simply a Weed with an Advertising Budget&rdquo;
Perception &gt; reality. Example: Stripe toothpaste cleans no betterâ€”but stripes signal &ldquo;advanced science&rdquo; to our brains.
ğŸª„For engineers: Data without storytelling is noise. Wrap logic in magic.
ğŸš« The Cost of Ignoring &ldquo;Alchemy&rdquo; in Tech Disengagement: Users tolerate &ldquo;logical&rdquo; UX but love &ldquo;irrational&rdquo; ones (e.g., Duolingoâ€™s absurd notifications). Team friction: Engineers who dismiss &ldquo;soft&rdquo; factors create solutions that are precisely wrong vs. vaguely right. Innovation stagnation: As Sutherland warns: &ldquo;Logic kills magic&rdquo;. Blockbuster died optimizing DVD logistics while Netflix sold nostalgia-in-a-red-envelope âœ¨. ğŸ’¥ Become a &ldquo;Psycho-Logical&rdquo; Engineer Test the &ldquo;irrational&rdquo;: Add whimsy to a feature (e.g., Slack /shrug). Measure and optimize for emotional response, not just KPIs. Reward &ldquo;alchemy&rdquo; in code reviews: Celebrate solutions that are human-elegant, not just machine-efficient. Study Kahneman + Sutherland as a duo: One gives you the map; the other hands you a machete to blaze new trails and be more impactful. &ldquo;To be brilliant, you have to be irrational.&rdquo; Rory Sutherland

